description:
Sometimes I connect a local {{mongos}} to our production environment to be able to debug something with live data. This is potentially risky if I forget this process and run our test suite later when I fixed the bug, which is why I have the following code in the module level of our test suite:
{code:title=tests/__init__.py|borderStyle=solid}
c = MongoClient("mongodb://localhost:27017")
if c.is_mongos:
    raise Exception("Connected to a local Mongos instance, need a mongod")
{code}

As of upgrading to pymongo 3, this will return False before a connection is established, making this check worthless for the purpose above. For now, I've added {{c.server_info()}} before the {{c.is_mongos}} check, but I really think it should raise an exception or ensure a connection before returning an answer. Have not checked the other is_* properties as I don't use them, but maybe the problem exists there as well.

Input:
{code}
_gen_find_command('collection', {'$query': {'foo': 1}, '$dumb': 2}, None,
                  0, 0, 0, None)
{code}
I believe the expected output is:
{code}
SON([('find', 'collection'), ('filter', {'foo': 1}), ('$dumb', 2)])
{code}
But the unrecognized $-option is omitted, *if* there is also a $query in the input:
{code}
SON([('find', 'collection'), ('filter', {'foo': 1})])
{code}

According to [the code|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-python-driver/blob/3.0/pymongo/collection.py#L762] the signature differs:
{code}
def find_one(self, filter=None, *args, **kwargs)
{code}

But in [the documentation|https://api.mongodb.org/python/3.0/api/pymongo/collection.html#pymongo.collection.Collection.find_one], find_one signature is:
{code}
find_one(filter_or_id=None, *args, **kwargs)
{code}

I check the error in version 3.0 and 3.2.2 (I assume then the error is for pymongo>=3.0)

We have a json encoder which overrides the default encoder so that timestamps are encoded as ISO-8601 strings ...

{noformat}
def our_default_encoder(obj):
    """Override the json encoder that comes with pymongo (bson)
    So that datetime objects are encoded as ISO-8601"""
    if isinstance(obj, datetime.datetime):
        iso = obj.isoformat()
        return {"$date": iso}
    return json_util.default(obj)
{noformat}

Even though the bson decoder in json_util parses some ISO-8601 strings it assumes that the seconds field contains 3 decimal places (i.e. milliseconds)

Could the object hook be augmented to parse a wider range of ISO-8601 timestamps? Possibly by ...

{noformat}
import iso8601

def object_hook(dct):
   ...
    if "$date" in dct:
        dtm = dct["$date"]
        if isinstance(dtm, string_type):
            dt = iso8601.parse_date(dtm)
            return dt
   ...
{noformat}

I have tested this against the current set of unittests and it appears to maintain the current behaviour and will parse strings generated by isoformat()
